'''Lamane''' or '''Laman''' (also ''Laam'' or ''Lam'') ''"master of the land"'' or ''"chief owner of the soil"'' in the [[Serer language]]<ref>Boul<U+00E8>gue, Jean. ''Le Grand Jolof, (XVIIIe - XVIe Si<U+00E8>cle).'' (Paris, Edition Fa<U+00E7>ades), Karthala (1987), p 30</ref><ref>Dyao, Yoro ''L<U+00E9>gendes et coutumes s<U+00E9>n<U+00E9>galaises.'' Cahiers de Yoro Dyao: publi<U+00E9>s et comment<U+00E9>s par Henri Gaden. p 12. (E. Leroux, 1912)</ref> were the [[landed gentry]] as well the title of ancient kings of the [[Serer people]] of [[Senegambia]] region which includes modern day [[Senegal]] and [[The Gambia]].<ref>Galvan, Dennis Charles,  ''The state must be our master of fire:'' p202. University of California Press, 2004. ISBN 0-520-23591-6</ref><ref>Dyao, Yoro ''L<U+00E9>gendes et coutumes s<U+00E9>n<U+00E9>galaises.'' Cahiers de Yoro Dyao: publi<U+00E9>s et comment<U+00E9>s par Henri Gaden. p 12. (E. Leroux, 1912)</ref> This Serer title was also [[loanword|loaned]] by the old kings of the [[Wolof people|Wolof]] kingdoms.<ref>Ajayi, J. F. Ade, Crowder, Michael, ''History of West Africa,'' p462. Longman, 1976</ref><ref>Boul<U+00E8>gue, Jean. ''Le Grand Jolof, (XVIIIe - XVIe Si<U+00E8>cle).'' (Paris, Edition Fa<U+00E7>ades), Karthala (1987), p 30</ref> The title is sometimes used interchangeably with the old title ''Maad'' or ''Mad''(sometimes Maat) (ancient Serer Kings).<ref>[[Roland Oliver|Oliver, Roland]], [[John Donnelly Fage|Fage, John Donnelly]], Sanderson, G. N, ''The Cambridge History of Africa,'' p214. Cambridge University Press, 1985. ISBN 0-521-22803-4</ref><ref>Ajayi, J. F. Ade & Crowder, Michael, ''History of West Africa,'' Volume 1, p 468. Published by: Longman, 1985. ISBN 0-582-64683-9</ref> These pre-[[Guelowar]] Lamanes should not be confused with the post-Guelowar Lamanes after  The Battle of Troubang 1335 (sometimes spelt: Turubang) which led to the Guelowars' migration to the [[Kingdom of Sine]] as [[refuge]]s.  The pre-Troubang (or Guelowar) Lamanes were kings whilst the post-Troubang Lamanes were merely provincial chiefs answerable to the King of Sine and [[Kingdom of Saloum|Saloum]].<ref>[[Alioune Sarr|Sarr, Alioune]], ''Histoire du Sine-Saloum.'' Introduction, bibliographie et Notes par Charles Becker, BIFAN, Tome 46, Serie B, n<U+00B0> 3-4, 1986-1987, p21</ref>

Although the post-Troubang Lamanes were always descendants of the ancient Serer village and town founders (the original Lamanes), and their families ruled the Kingdoms of Sine, Saloum and [[Baol]] etc., the power they previously enjoyed as Lamanes became diminished post-Troubang but were still titled and made up the  class of the [[landed gentry]].<ref>Saint-Martin, Yves-Jean, ''Le S<U+00E9>n<U+00E9>gal sous le Second Empire,'' Karthala (2000), pp. 35 & 610. ISBN 2-86537-201-4</ref>  Though their power was somewhat diminished, their economic and political power was intricately linked to Serer custom, Serer history and [[Serer religion]].  As such, they were extremely powerful if not as true kings after Troubang (1335), as guardians of Serer traditions and beliefs and could dethrone a reigning [[monarch]] if threatened.<ref>Kesteloot, Lilyan, ''Dieux d'eau du Sahel : voyage <U+00E0> travers les mythes, de Seth <U+00E0> Tyamaba,'' L'Harmattan, Paris, ; IFAN, Dakar, 2007, p. 123 (ISBN 978-2-296-04384-8)</ref><ref>Ngom, Biram <U+00C9>thiopiques (revue), num<U+00E9>ro 54, nouvelle s<U+00E9>rie, vol. 7,  semestre 1991</ref>

==The Great Council of Lamanes==
The Great Council of Lamanes was an ancient Council made up of Serer Lamanes (Kings) who divided the [[Senegambia|Senegambia Region]] into ''Lamanats'' (provinces or kingdoms) which they ruled. They were the Lamanic class.<ref>[[Henry Gravrand|Gravrand, Henry]], ''La Civilisation Sereer - Cosaan, Les origines.'' pp 295-6 & 303. Nouvelles Editions africaines, 1983. ISBN 2-7236-0877-8</ref><ref>Ngom, Biram, <U+00C9>thiopiques (revue), num<U+00E9>ro 54, nouvelle s<U+00E9>rie, vol. 7,  semestre 1991</ref> One of their [[constitutional]] duties were to hear [[legal cases]] like a [[Court of Appeal]]. It was the highest appallate court in Serer country.<ref>Ngom, Biram, <U+00C9>thiopiques (revue), num<U+00E9>ro 54, nouvelle s<U+00E9>rie, vol. 7,  semestre 1991</ref> The first Guelowar king in Sine Maysa Wali  commonly known as Maysa Wali Jon was [[legal advisor]] to this Council for 15 years before his nomination and election as King of [[Kingdom of Sine|Sine]].  It was this Council that granted his family (the [[Guelowar]]s) [[Right of asylum|asylum]] after their defeat by the Nyanthio (variation : [[<U+00D1>aanco]]) [[dynasty]] of [[Kaabu]] at Troubang (a dynastic war between the [[royal houses]] of Guelowar and Nyanthio).<ref>Ngom, Biram, <U+00C9>thiopiques (revue), num<U+00E9>ro 54, nouvelle s<U+00E9>rie, vol. 7,  semestre 1991</ref><ref>Gravrand, Henry, ''La Civilisation Sereer - Cosaan, Les origines,'' pp 295-6. Nouvelles Editions africaines, 1983. ISBN 2-7236-0877-8</ref>

==Some prominent Serer Lamanes==
===Lamanes before the Battle of Troubang (1335)===
*[[Lamane Jegan Joof]] (English spelling in [[Gambia]]; ''Djigan Diouf'' French spelling in [[Senegal]] or ''Jegaan  Juuf'' [[Serer language|Serer]] spelling) - the c. 11th century founder and King of [[Tukar]] and [[Njujuf]] originally from [[Lambaye Arrondissement|Lambaye]] in modern day [[Senegal]].  His historical account and that of Tukar is part of Senegal's [[national curriculum]].<ref>Galvan, Dennis Charles, The State Must be our Master of Fire, pp108-111, 122, 304 (pp. 2-281), University of California Press, 2004. ISBN 0-520-23591-6</ref><ref>Bressers, Hans & Rosenbaum, Walter A., ''Achieving sustainable development: the challenge of governance across social scales,'' Greenwood Publishing Group, 2003, p. 151 ISBN 0275978028</ref><ref>Joint Center for African Studies. Conference, University of California, Berkeley, [[Stanford University]]. Stanford-Berkeley Joint Center for African Studies Annual Conference: papers, Volume 2, p 14. Joint Center for African Studies., 1995</ref>
*Lamane Jaw (or Lamane Diao) - King of [[Jolof]] 1285<ref>Nnoli, Okwudiba, ''Ethnic conflicts in Africa,'' p241. CODESRIA, 1998. ISBN 2-86978-070-2</ref>

===Lamanes during and after the Guelwar period (1350-1969)===
The [[Guelowar]] period starts from 1350 during the reign of Maysa Wali in [[Kingdom of Sine|Sine]] and ended in 1969 after the death of both king of Sine and [[Kingdom of Saloum|Saloum]] - [[Maad a Sinig Mahecor Joof]] and [[Maad Saloum Fode N'Gouye Joof]] respectively.<ref>Sarr, Alioune, ''Histoire du Sine-Saloum'' (S<U+00E9>n<U+00E9>gal). Introduction, bibliographie et notes par Charles Becker. Version l<U+00E9>g<U+00E8>rement remani<U+00E9>e par rapport <U+00E0> celle qui est parue en 1986-87. p 21</ref><ref>Klein, Martin A., ''Islam and Imperialism in Senegal Sine-Saloum, 1847-1914,'' Edinburgh University Press (1968). p XV</ref>

*Lamane Pangha Yaya Sarr (many variations: ''Penga Yaye Sarr'' etc.) - c. 14th century Lamane of [[Kingdom of Sine|Sine]] and an opponent to the Guelowar refuges.<ref>Ngom, Biram, <U+00C9>thiopiques (revue), num<U+00E9>ro 54, nouvelle s<U+00E9>rie, vol. 7,  semestre 1991</ref><ref>Diouf, Niokhobaye. "Chronique du royaume du Sine." Suivie de notes sur les traditions orales et les sources <U+00E9>crites concernant le royaume du Sine par Charles Becker et Victor Martin. (1972). Bulletin de l'Ifan, Tome 34, S<U+00E9>rie B, n<U+00B0> 4, (1972). pp 706-708</ref>

